**TypeScript**

TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing and other features to improve the development experience. It was created by Microsoft in 2012 and is widely used for building large-scale JavaScript applications.

TypeScript compiles to JavaScript, which means you can run your TypeScript code in any browser or Node.js environment that supports ECMAScript 3 or higher. The TypeScript compiler checks your code for errors and warnings at compile-time, rather than at runtime, which helps you catch type-related issues early on.

TypeScript adds several features to JavaScript, including:

1. **Type annotations**: You can add type annotations to your code to specify the expected data type of a variable, function parameter, or property. This helps catch type errors at compile-time rather than at runtime.
2. **Interfaces**: TypeScript introduces the concept of interfaces, which are a way to define a blueprint of an object's shape, including its properties and methods.
3. **Classes**: TypeScript supports classes, which are a more traditional OOP approach to defining objects.
4. **Modules**: TypeScript supports ES6 modules, which allow you to organize your code into reusable modules.

The benefits of using TypeScript include:

* **Better code maintainability**: With type annotations and interfaces, it's easier to understand the structure and behavior of your code.
* **Fewer runtime errors**: TypeScript's type system helps catch errors before your code is executed, making it easier to debug.
* **Improved code completion**: Many IDEs and code editors provide better code completion suggestions when using TypeScript.

**Duck Typing**

Duck typing is a concept that originated in the Ruby world and has been adopted by some JavaScript developers, including those using TypeScript.

The term "duck typing" comes from the idea that if it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, it's a duck. In other words, if an object behaves like another object or conforms to a certain interface, it's considered to be of the same type, even if it doesn't have the same declared type.

In TypeScript, duck typing is not a formal type system, but rather a flexible way to work with objects that don't have explicit type annotations. When you use duck typing, you're relying on the object's properties and methods to determine its type, rather than its declared type.

For example:
```typescript
interface Printable {
  print(): void;
}

class Document implements Printable {
  print() {
    console.log("Printing a document...");
  }
}

class Image implements Printable {
  print() {
    console.log("Printing an image...");
  }
}

function printSomething(printable: Printable) {
  printable.print();
}

// Using duck typing
const(doc: any) = new Document();
printSomething(doc); // prints "Printing a document..."

const img: any = new Image();
printSomething(img); // prints "Printing an image..."
```
In this example, we define an interface `Printable` with a single method `print()`. We then create two classes `Document` and `Image` that implement this interface. The `printSomething()` function takes a `Printable` object as an argument.

When we pass an instance of `Document` or `Image` to `printSomething()`, it works because both objects have a `print()` method, even though they don't have explicit type annotations. This is an example of duck typing in action.

While duck typing can be useful for quick prototyping or working with legacy code, it's generally recommended to use type annotations and interfaces when possible to take advantage of TypeScript's type system and improve code maintainability.

In summary, TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing and other features to improve development, while duck typing is a flexible approach to working with objects that don't have explicit type annotations, relying on their properties and methods to determine their type.

Here is an example code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command `ban`:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildPresences,
  ],
});

client.commands = new Map();

const banCommand = {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a member from the server',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'The user to ban',
      type: 'user',
      required: true,
    },
    {
      name: 'reason',
      description: 'The reason for the ban',
      type: 'string',
      required: false,
    },
  ],
  execute: async (interaction) => {
    const member = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';
    const guild = interaction.guild;

    if (!guild.members.cache.has(member.id)) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'User not found in this guild.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    try {
      await guild.members.ban(member, { reason });
      interaction.reply({ content: `${member.tag} has been banned.` });
    } catch (error) {
      interaction.reply({ content: 'Error banning user.', ephemeral: true });
    }
  },
};

client.commands.set('ban', banCommand);

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log('Ready!');
});

client.once('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const { command } = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);

  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    await interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error while executing this command.', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN');
```

Make sure to replace `YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token from the Discord Developer Portal.

This code sets up a bot with a single slash command `/ban`. The command takes a user and an optional reason as input, and bans the user from the guild. The bot logs an error message if something goes wrong.

Remember to register your bot in the Discord Developer Portal and set up the intended guilds and permissions before running this code.

Here's a simple implementation of a function that converts Markdown to HTML using the `std::regex` library for pattern matching. This implementation supports basic Markdown formatting such as headings, bold text, italics, links, and paragraphs.

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

const std::string MARKDOWN_HEADER_PATTERN = "^#{1,6} (.*)$";
const std::string MARKDOWN_BOLD_PATTERN = "(火)\\*([^\*]+)\*(火)";
const std::string MARKDOWN_ITALIC_PATTERN = "(火)_([^_]+)_(火)";
const std::string MARKDOWN_LINK_PATTERN = "\\[(.*)\\]\\((.*)\\)";
const std::string MARKDOWN_PARAGRAPH_PATTERN = "^([^\n]+)(\n|$)";

std::string convertMarkdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::string line;

    // headings
    std::smatch match;
    std::regex_search(markdown, match, std::regex(MARKDOWN_HEADER_PATTERN));
    while (!match.empty()) {
        std::string headerText = match[1].str;
        html += "<h" + std::to_string(match.length() - 1) + ">";

        // links
        std::regex_search(headerText, match, std::regex(MARKDOWN_LINK_PATTERN));
        while (!match.empty()) {
            std::string linkText = match[1].str;
            std::string linkUrl = match[2].str;
            headerText = std::regex_replace(headerText, std::regex("(" + linkText + ")", linkUrl);
            match.clear();
        }

        // bold and italics
        headerText = std::regex_replace(headerText, std::regex(MARKDOWN_BOLD_PATTERN), "<strong>$2</strong>");
        headerText = std::regex_replace(headerText, std::regex(MARKDOWN_ITALIC_PATTERN), "<em>$2</em>");

        html += headerText + "</h" + std::to_string(match.length() - 1) + ">";
        match.clear();
        markdown.replace(0, match.position(), "");
        markdown.erase(match.position() + match.length());
    }

    // paragraphs
    std::stringstream ss(markdown);
    std::string paragraph;
    while (std::getline(ss, line)) {
        if (!line.empty()) {
            html += "<p>" + line + "</p>";
        }
    }

    // remove trailing whitespace from lines
    return html;
}
```

You can use this function like this:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Heading\n# Heading with *bold* and _italics_[http://example.com](http://example.com)";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```
<h1>Heading</h1><h1><a href="http://example.com">Heading with <strong>bold</strong> and <em>italics</em></a></h1>
```

Remember that this is a basic implementation and may not support all Markdown features. For more advanced Markdown support, consider using a dedicated Markdown library such as `pugligh-markdown` or `CommonMark`. 

Here's how you can use it:

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

std::string convertMarkdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_node root = doc.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "html");
    root.append_child(pugi::node_type::element, "body");
